<$transclude $tiddler="$:/plugins/rimir/doc-template/templates/page">
<$fill $name="body">

!! Does the layout reflow on small screens?

No. Tiles use absolute pixel coordinates, so a free-form dashboard is desktop-first and does not reflow to narrow viewports. This is inherent to the free-form model.

!! A tile shows nothing / only raw text — why?

A tile transcludes the target tiddler's body. Tiddlers whose visible display comes from ViewTemplate //segments// rather than their body — and stream-typed tiddlers, whose `text` field is empty — render thin in a tile. Point the tile at a tiddler with body content, or use a transclusion-bearing wrapper as the target.

!! What is the difference between the ⧉ popup and clicking a tile to open it?

Clicking a tile ''navigates'' to the target in the story river (leaving the dashboard view). The ⧉ //show contents// control instead opens the target in a centered popup ''on top of'' the dashboard, rendered through the default ViewTemplate — so you can read the full tiddler (title, tags, fields and body) without losing your place. Close it with × or by clicking the backdrop.

!! Can the same tiddler appear on more than one tile?

Yes. A tile is just a tiddler with a `target` field, so nothing stops several tiles — anywhere on the dashboard or across its groups — from pointing at the same target. The quickest way to make one is to hold ''Ctrl'' (or ''Cmd'') while you start dragging a tile: that drops a copy where you release instead of moving the original.

!! How do I put tiles into a group, and nest groups?

Press ''Add group'' for a container tile, then either drop tiddlers from the wiki onto its canvas or drag existing tiles into it. A group's ＋ control adds a group //inside// it, and you can also drag a whole group into another — nesting is recursive with no depth limit. Drag a tile (or group) back onto the root canvas to take it out again.

!! I expanded a group but another tile covers it — how do I keep it on top?

Expanding a group already raises it to the front (its `z` becomes the highest on the dashboard), so its contents sit above the other tiles. If you later move or resize a //different// tile, that tile comes to the front in turn and may overlap the group again — just click the group's ▾/▸ toggle (or move it) to raise it back.

!! What happens to the tiles inside a group when I delete the group?

They are not deleted. Removing a group (its × control) promotes its direct children up to the group's own container — so a group at the top level spills its contents onto the dashboard, and a nested group spills into its parent group. Delete the child tiles individually if you want them gone.

!! Why did my tile snap to a new position when I dragged it into a group?

Positions are relative to the container. When a tile moves into (or out of) a group its coordinates are recomputed relative to the new canvas, so it keeps roughly the on-screen spot where you dropped it rather than its old numbers.

!! How do I switch a tile between window and bare?

Use the ⊟ action in the tile's ⋮ menu (the corner cluster revealed on hover). It toggles the tile's `style` field.

!! How do I open a tile's link in a new browser tab?

If the tile's target tiddler has a `url` or `_canonical_uri` field, the tile shows an ↗ action in its ⋮ menu, and ''Ctrl/Cmd-clicking'' the tile does the same — it opens that address in a new browser tab. A plain click still opens the target //inside the wiki//. This is how an uploaded image or file tile (which carries `_canonical_uri`) opens its raw file. The fields consulted and their priority are set in `$:/config/rimir/dashboard/external-open-fields` (default `url _canonical_uri`, first non-empty wins); edit it to add your own field or change the order. Absolute URLs open as-is; a bare host gets `https://` prepended.

!! Can a tile show a tiddler's icon (or some other field) instead of its body?

Yes. By default a tile shows the target's body, but if the target has no (or empty) `text` and an `icon`, the tile shows the icon automatically. To choose explicitly, open the tile's ⋮ menu and pick under //Show//: ''auto'' (the default), ''body'', ''icon'', or type any field name. That sets the tile's `display` field.

To do it for many tiles at once, use ''display rules'' on the dashboard: click //Display rules//, then add a row like `[tag[Image]] ⇒ _canonical_uri` or `[has[icon]] ⇒ icon`. The first rule (by order) whose filter selects a tile's target decides what that tile shows — unless the tile has its own //Show// choice, which always wins. If the chosen field's value points at an image/SVG tiddler it is transcluded; otherwise the field's value is rendered as-is.

!! Clicking a bare tile opens the tiddler instead of interacting with its content — is that expected?

Yes. Bare tiles are previews: their content is non-interactive (`pointer-events: none`) so the whole box reliably acts as move / open surface. Use a window tile when you need to interact with the content.

!! Where is my dashboard's layout stored?

In the tile tiddlers under `$:/config/rimir/dashboard/<dashId>/tiles/…`. They sync to disk like any `$:/config` tiddler. Deleting a dashboard does not delete its tiles automatically — remove them by prefix if you want them gone.

!! Do dashboards nest?

You can point a tile at another dashboard tiddler; it will render that dashboard's canvas inside the tile. Deeply nested dashboards are untested — treat as an edge case.

!! Can a tile show the kind type icon?

Yes — automatically. If a window tile's target is a [[rimir/kind|$:/plugins/rimir/kind]] instance, the type's icon appears before the caption with the type name as hover text. It requires nothing beyond having kind installed and a `kind.icon` on the type; without kind, the icon is simply omitted. (Bare tiles have no title bar, so no icon is shown there.)

!! Nothing happens when I drag — the tile just gets selected/dragged as text.

That is a sign the drag region isn't arming (for example an element accidentally marked `.rr-dash-no-drag`). Move starts only on the handle (window) or the box (bare); resize only on the corner grip.

